        "D. 40.2%",
        "A. 11.1%",
        "B. 20.5%",
        "C. 30.1%"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Benford's Law predicts that in naturally occurring numerical datasets, the digit '1' appears as the leading digit approximately 30.1% of the time. Per CFE Manual, this logarithmic distribution pattern applies to many financial datasets and deviations may indicate data manipulation or fraud requiring further investigation.",
      "justification_wrong": "11.1% would represent uniform distribution where all digits appear equally. 20.5% and 40.2% do not align with Benford's logarithmic formula. The mathematical expectation for leading digit '1' is specifically 30.1%, making significant deviations from this benchmark potential fraud indicators in financial data analysis.",
