      "question": "A forensic accountant is analyzing sales data from a retail company's point-of-sale system using SQL queries. The accountant needs to identify potential revenue manipulation by comparing daily sales patterns across multiple store locations. Which of the following SQL-based analytical approaches would be MOST effective in detecting unusual revenue patterns that might indicate fraud?\n\nA) Using UNION clauses to combine sales data from different periods and calculating simple averages for each store location\n\nB) Implementing window functions with PARTITION BY store location and ORDER BY date to calculate rolling averages, standard deviations, and identify outliers that deviate significantly from expected patterns\n\nC) Creating INNER JOIN statements to match sales transactions with inventory records and sorting results alphabetically by product name\n\nD) Using basic SELECT statements with WHERE clauses to filter transactions above a fixed dollar threshold and manually reviewing each transaction",
