      "topic": "Data Analytics - Continuous Auditing & Monitoring",
      "question": "A company has implemented a continuous auditing system to monitor purchase transactions. The system flags transactions for review based on predefined rules. Which of the following scenarios would MOST likely indicate a weakness in the continuous monitoring system's design?\n\nA. The system generates alerts for all purchase orders exceeding $50,000, resulting in 15-20 alerts per day that require management review.\n\nB. The system identifies duplicate vendor payments by matching vendor name, amount, and date, but fails to detect the same invoice paid to vendors with slightly different name variations (e.g., \"ABC Company\" vs. \"ABC Co.\").\n\nC. The system monitors employee expense reimbursements and flags those exceeding monthly limits, with exceptions reviewed and approved by the CFO within 48 hours.\n\nD. The system performs daily reconciliations between inventory records and sales transactions, generating exception reports that are reviewed weekly by the controller.",
      "correct_answer": "B",
      "explanation": "Option B represents a significant design weakness in the continuous monitoring system. Duplicate payment detection that relies solely on exact name matching will fail to identify fraudulent schemes where perpetrators intentionally create vendor variations to bypass controls. Effective continuous monitoring systems should incorporate fuzzy matching algorithms, vendor ID validation, and other techniques to identify substantially similar vendors.\n\nOption A describes a functioning control that generates a manageable volume of alerts for review. Option C demonstrates proper monitoring with timely exception approval. Option D shows regular reconciliation and review, though weekly review might be enhanced with more frequent monitoring. Only option B describes a fundamental design flaw that would allow fraudulent transactions to go undetected.",
